==English==

===Pronunciation===
*ro͞ot
* {{IPA|/ɹuːt/}}
* {{audio|en-us-root.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* Rhymes: [[Rhymes:English:-uːt|-uːt]]

====Homophones====
*[[route]] {{italbrac|Commonwealth English}}

===Etymology===
From Middle English ''root'', the underground part of a plant, from late Old English ''[[rot|rōt]]'', from Old Norse ''[[rōt]]'', from Proto-Germanic ''[[*wrot]]'', from Proto-Indo-European ''*wrd-'', root; cognate with '''[[wort]]''' and '''[[radix]]'''

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# The part of a plant, generally underground, that absorbs water and nutrients.
# The part of a tooth extending into the bone holding the tooth in place.
# The part of a hair under the skin that holds the hair in place.
# Source.
#: ''The love of money is the '''root''' of all evil''
# {{arithmetic}} Of a number or expression, a number which, when raised to a specified power, yields the specified number or expression.
#: ''The cube '''root''' of 27 is 3.''
# {{arithmetic}} A [[square root]] (understood if no power is specified; in which case, “the root of” is often abbreviated to “root”).
#: ''Multiply by '''root''' 2.''
# {{analysis}} A [[zero]] (of a [[function]]).
# {{graphtheory}}, {{computing}} The single node of a [[tree]] that has no parent.
# {{italbrac|philology}} A word from which another word or words are derived.
# {{italbrac|Australian coarse slang}} An act of [[sexual intercourse]].
# {{italbrac|Australian coarse slang}} A sexual partner.
# {{computing}} In [[UNIX]] terminology, the first user account with complete access to the operating system and its configuration, found at the root of the directory structure.
# {{computing}} The person who manages accounts on a UNIX system.

=====Usage notes=====
*The Australian sexual senses of ''root'' is somewhat milder than ''[[fuck]]'' but still quite coarse, certainly not for polite conversation. The normal usage is ''to have a root'' or similar<!--, and generally no confusion or [[double entendre]] arises in other uses like “tree root” or “root cause”-->.

